            {
              "originalPosition": 59,
              "body": "You are using Unicode [below](https://github.com/lwig-wg/terminology/blob/a413894e1a43f67ef3ac7ac71f7912cafc31afa6/draft-ietf-iotops-7228bis.md?plain=1#L959-L960) already. Why not use it here as well like this \"10\u00b9\u2070\u2070\"?",
              "createdAt": "2025-10-23T10:45:49Z",
              "updatedAt": "2025-10-23T11:29:11Z"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "PRR_kwDOBMYTbM7I2Lb3",
          "commit": {
            "abbreviatedOid": "a413894"
          },
          "author": "cabo",
          "authorAssociation": "CONTRIBUTOR",
          "state": "COMMENTED",
          "body": "",
          "createdAt": "2025-10-23T12:16:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2025-10-23T12:16:31Z",
          "comments": [
            {
              "originalPosition": 59,
              "body": "Good question.  \r\n\r\nThe manuscript is translated into a single XML form, which is then rendered in plain text, HTML, and PDF.\r\nSo there needs to be a common representation of the superscript in all three.\r\nRFCXML provides the <sup element, which shows the fallback given for plaintext rendering.\r\n\r\nIf we didn't want to use RFCXML <sup superscripts, we would have to check the characters in the superscript:\r\nOnly a limited set of characters have a superscript variant in Unicode.  \r\n\r\nWhile all characters used in a superscript in the current document happen to do, the characters \u00b9\u00b2\u00b3 come from the Latin-1 supplement (U+00Bx) while the characters \u2070\u2074\u2075\u2076\u2077\u2078\u2079\u207b come from Superscripts and Subscripts (U+207x).\r\nIn a number of fonts, the appearances of these two ranges inexplicably do not match.\r\nSo HTML and PDF would often look ugly to enable better plaintext looks.",
              "createdAt": "2025-10-23T12:16:31Z",
              "updatedAt": "2025-10-23T12:16:31Z"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
